  "body": "The way we are applying the builder default config is a bit counterintuitive and can lead to confusion.\r\n\r\n```json\r\n{\r\n  \"default_config\": {\r\n    \"fee_recipient\": \"0xf0...\",\r\n    \"builder\": {\r\n      \"enabled\": true,\r\n      \"gas_limit\": \"12345654321\"\r\n    }\r\n  },\r\n  \"proposer_config\": {\r\n    \"0xb8...\": {\r\n      \"fee_recipient\": \"0xd23...\"\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn the example above, builder will be not enabled to the `0xb8...` key but it will for all other keys. While it make sense in term of simplicity it may be counterintuitive.\r\n\r\nI'm prone to move to an \"override layers\" approach where each value is taken as the first non-empty value from the sequence:\r\n\r\n1. pubkey specific\r\n   1. from runtime config\r\n   2. from from proposer config\r\n3. from `default_config`\r\n4. from a CLI argument\r\n5. hardcoded default value\r\n\r\nif we enforce that `default_config` MUST have a `fee_recipient`, the other values could be optional and applied following the rule above.\r\n",
